<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1870-09-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1870-09-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="35" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d35">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 35.</note>
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Fish</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                E. B. Washburne</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 175.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi><hi rend="italic"> Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1870-09-27"><hi rend="italic">September</hi> 27, 1870.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>Referring to your No. 280, relating to the political occurrences at
                            Paris, on the 4th instant, and inclosing a translation into French of
                            your letter to Mr. Jules Favre, as it appeared in the French press, it
                            is only necessary for me to state that the action thus reported has
                            already received the approval of this Department and of the people of
                            the United States.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>HAMILTON FISH.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>